# Project Structure

## lib/ naming
- Domains with multiple files get a subdirectory: `lib/auth/`, `lib/supabase/`
- Within a named subdirectory, generic names are correct: `actions.ts`, `server.ts`, `browser.ts` — the directory provides the namespace
- Standalone concerns stay flat with a descriptive name: `lib/prisma.ts`, `lib/utils.ts`
- Never prefix a file with its parent directory name (e.g. `lib/auth/auth-actions.ts` is wrong; `lib/auth/actions.ts` is correct)

## Supabase client selection
| Context | Import |
|---|---|
| Browser / Client Component | `@/lib/supabase/browser` |
| Server Component / Action / Route Handler | `@/lib/supabase/server` |
| Next.js middleware | `@/lib/supabase/middleware` |

## Import rules
- Always use `@/` alias — never relative paths that cross the `src/` boundary
- Import components from `@/components/<name>` (our wrappers), **never** from `@/components/ui/<name>` directly
- `src/components/ui/` is ShadCN-generated — treat it as read-only; all customisation goes in the wrapper

## Third-party library abstraction

**Always wrap third-party libraries behind a single abstraction layer.**

If the library is ever swapped out, only the wrapper changes — not every file that uses it.

### Where wrappers live
| Type | Location | Example |
|---|---|---|
| UI component library | `src/components/<name>.tsx` | `components/button.tsx` wraps ShadCN |
| Utility / logic library | `src/lib/<domain>.ts` or `src/lib/<domain>/index.ts` | `lib/validation.ts` wraps Zod |

### Example — validation library (Zod)
```typescript
// src/lib/validation.ts  ← the only file that imports from "zod"
import { z } from "zod";

export { z };
export type { ZodSchema, ZodError } from "zod";

export const emailSchema = z.string().email("Invalid email address");
export const passwordSchema = z.string().min(8, "Password must be at least 8 characters");

// Shared parse helper — swap the library here without touching callers
export function parseSchema<T>(schema: z.ZodSchema<T>, data: unknown) {
  return schema.safeParse(data);
}
```

Callers import from `@/lib/validation`, never directly from `"zod"`. If Zod is later replaced with Valibot or Yup, only `lib/validation.ts` changes.

### What to wrap
- Validation libraries (Zod, Valibot, Yup)
- Date/time libraries (date-fns, dayjs, Temporal)
- Analytics / tracking (Posthog, Segment)
- Email providers (Resend, Nodemailer)
- File storage helpers (beyond the Supabase client)
- Any library likely to be upgraded or swapped in future

### What NOT to wrap
Standard library utilities and stable, low-level packages that have no realistic swap candidate (e.g. `clsx`, `tailwind-merge` — already wrapped inside `lib/utils.ts`).

## Input as a full form field
`@/components/input` is the complete form field component — it renders a label, the input, and a per-field error in one unit. Use `validate` for shorthand HTML5 constraint attributes:

```tsx
// Bare input (no label/error) — same as always
<Input name="q" type="search" placeholder="Search…" />

// Full field with label, validation, and per-field error
<Input
  id="email"
  name="email"
  label="Email"
  placeholder="you@example.com"
  validate="email"           // sets type, autoComplete, required automatically
  error={fieldErrors?.email}
/>

// With a label action (e.g. "Forgot password?" link)
<Input id="password" name="password" label="Password" validate="password"
  labelAction={<Link href="/forgot-password">Forgot password?</Link>} />
```

Available `validate` values: `required` · `email` · `password` · `new-password` · `url` · `tel` · `number`

## When adding a new ShadCN component
1. Run `npx shadcn@latest add <component>` — it lands in `src/components/ui/`
2. Immediately create a wrapper in `src/components/<name>.tsx` that re-exports it
3. Use only the wrapper everywhere in the app
